## Phase 2: Train a ML model to predict LST at native MODIS resolution.

In this phase, we build a model that can understand how surface
characteristics influence land surface temperature.

To do that we combine three datasets:

1.  **MODIS LST**

    This is our target variable (what we want to predict)

2.  **Sentinel-2 multispectral image composite**

    A multispectral image composite is made up of multiple individual
    satellite images to best mask out clouds and remove outlier
    observations. We use the Sentinel-2 data to extract information
    about water, vegetation, soil and built areas because they all
    affect heat.

3.  **Digital surface model (DSM)**

    This gives us information about elevation, building heights and
    local topography. Each of these influence shading, ventilation and
    sun exposure.

```{python}
modis = rxr.open_rasterio("modelling_data/MODIS_images/MODIS_LST_20250717_1255.tif", masked=True).assign_coords(band=["LST"])

s2    = rxr.open_rasterio("modelling_data/original_resolution/S2_composite.tif", masked=True).assign_coords(band=["B","G","R","NIR","SWIR1","SWIR2"])

dsm   = rxr.open_rasterio("modelling_data/original_resolution/DSM.tif", masked=True).assign_coords(band=["DSM"])

ds_modis = modis.to_dataset(dim="band")
ds_s2 = s2.to_dataset(dim="band")
ds_dsm = dsm.to_dataset(dim="band")

# Combine into one dataset
ds = xr.merge([ds_modis, ds_s2, ds_dsm])
```

